snippet.textDisplay:
You'll never convince me 8k is useful for the average home user (unless the "average" user in 5 years has 80" screens in personal theater/gaming rooms). Heck, even 4k is probably pushing it for most. I'd be willing to bet the other tech in new displays is a bigger improvement (like OLED was, etc) than straight resolution.

However, if the Scarlet can reliably do 4k at never less than 60fps, that'd still be a solid improvement. Pushing to 120fps would be awesome, but I think that's where the focus should more be at and not this crazy race for more and more raw resolution on the end user side.
snippet.textOriginal:
You'll never convince me 8k is useful for the average home user (unless the "average" user in 5 years has 80" screens in personal theater/gaming rooms). Heck, even 4k is probably pushing it for most. I'd be willing to bet the other tech in new displays is a bigger improvement (like OLED was, etc) than straight resolution.

However, if the Scarlet can reliably do 4k at never less than 60fps, that'd still be a solid improvement. Pushing to 120fps would be awesome, but I think that's where the focus should more be at and not this crazy race for more and more raw resolution on the end user side.
